28-year-old cook found dead in San Francisco shopping mall
The 28-year-old chef, who recently moved to San Francisco, was found dead in a stairway through a local shopping mall this week.
However, the victim’s brother says he can’t imagine someone wanting to hurt him, noting, “Finally, things were going well for him.”
"The body found in Westfield Mall on Wednesday morning was identified as a 28-year-old San Francisco resident, Frank Galicia," the San Francisco Forensic Medical Examination Bureau said in a statement.
The San Francisco Police Department reports that the death was classified as a murder and the investigation is ongoing.
The victim’s brother, Luis Galicia, told ABC’s KGO in San Francisco that Frank, a past Boston delivery line cook, got his dream job as a cook at San Francisco’s Sons & Daughters six months ago.
Sons & Daughters said they were "shocked and depressed" by his death.
"We are a small team that works as a friendly family and he will be greatly missed," the spokesman said.
Our thoughts and condolences to Frank’s family and friends during this difficult time.
Luis Galizia said Frank first stayed at the hostels, but recently "he's finally done fine."
“He found an apartment, he was dating a girl,” Luis Galicia told KGO.
Luis Galicia said he couldn’t imagine someone who would want to hurt his younger brother.
He had a good heart and a good soul.
His way of connecting with the family has always been to prepare us some dish, to prepare us dinner,” said Luis Galicia.
He never wanted to be involved in a fight.
He was a brother who sailed along the river.
“With all the bad things happening to this world, it was that untapped diamond that shone brightly every day,” he said.
Anyone who has the information is asked to call the SFPD Hotline at 415-575-4444.
