Scientists have found an animal that can live 500 years.
An international team of biologists has concluded that the longest-lived vertebrate animal is the Greenlandic polar shark, which can live about 500 years.
Scientists conducted a radiocarbon analysis of the crystals of the eyes of 28 Greenland sharks.
The largest shark, whose length exceeds five meters, can be from 272 to 512 years.
Biologists believe that low metabolism plays an important role in shark longevity, which leads to slow development.
Female Greenland sharks reach sexual maturity only by the age of 150.
Previously, it was believed that the longest of all vertebrate animals is the "neighbor" of the shark - the Greenland whale.
The oldest specimen known to scientists was just over 210 years old.
