As a result of the attack, four people died and 19 were injured.
The epicenter of the explosions hit the city of Hua Hin.
Among the victims were ten foreigners, citizens of four states, there are no Russians among them.
None of the terrorist groups has yet claimed responsibility for the incident, but the country’s interior ministry has hastened to state that the Islamists were not involved.
Several people have already been arrested on suspicion of organizing the explosions.
According to preliminary data from the local police, the scale and characteristics of the explosions indicate that they were directed against the country's leading military.
Attacks have occurred at popular tourist resorts, including Patong Beach in the Phuket area and Hua Hin, Trang and Surat Thani.
Since the military junta came to power in 2014, economic growth has fallen from 7.2% (2012) to 2.8% (2015), but tourism has remained one of the few industries to show development.
In 2016, the country was visited by 14 million people, which is 1.5 million more than in 2015.
The first suspects in the preparation and organization of attacks have already been detained, police colonel Krisana Patanacharoen said.
It is too early to talk about the goals, he added, but the country's interior ministry "is convinced that they are not related to international extremist groups".
“It’s too early to draw conclusions,” Patanacharoen said.
But we know with certainty that these incidents are not directly related to any kind of terrorism, they are actually local diversions, and we are trying to establish the identities of those behind them.
The explosions occurred on the birthday of Queen Sikrit of Thailand.
The Thai junta considers the protection of the monarchy one of its top priorities, so the incident is likely directed against it.
According to police general Sithich Shrisopacharoenrat, the bombs were detonated remotely with a difference of half an hour.
