The new system has been adopted and will be tested for the first time in the 2017 parliamentary elections.
On May 22, 2014, a military coup d'état took place in Thailand under the leadership of the country's army commander Prayut Chan-ocha.
In this step, he said, the army was driven by an ongoing political crisis and lack of progress in the negotiations between the government and the opposition.
The military created the National Council for Peace and Order, introduced the ruling clock and censorship, dispersed the protesters and the upper house of parliament.
