The Muslim Spiritual Authority (DUM) of Tatarstan refuses to use the Russian language in mosques.
Yesterday, the DUM plenary ordered its imams to preach Friday sermons only in Tatar to force young Tatars to “learn their native language.”
The administration said that this "in no way violates" the rights of Muslims of other nationalities.
In some mosques, Kazan mourns that up to 60% of parishioners do not understand the Tatar language, including foreign students, migrants and the Tatars themselves.
Imams fear that their sermons in Tatar "will not reach the whole audience".
Yesterday, the plenary of the DUM of Tatarstan unanimously decided to hold Friday sermons in the mosques of the Republic only in the Tatar language.
According to Tatarstan mufti Kamil Samigullin, this should be an incentive for young Tatars to “learn their native language”.
"For those who will say that it is "heavy", in every large mosque we intend to organize lessons in the Tatar language absolutely free of charge," - promised Mr. Samigullin.
He added that "the decision has already entered into force" and today in all mosques of the sermon "must be already in the Tatar language".
He recalled that the DUM of Tatarstan publishes the magazine "Shura" with typical sermons in the Tatar language.
The imam, who does not speak Tatar well enough, "can thoroughly prepare for them".
DUM of Tatarstan unites more than a thousand parishes in all the municipalities of the republic.
According to the Mufti, Friday sermons are exclusively in Tatar.
At the same time, the Russian language was used in a number of mosques in Kazan.
In particular, as Mufti pointed out, this was practiced in the Bournaev Mosque, Zakabanna and Eniler.
However, Mr. Muhammetshin stressed, management sets the task that all students should speak both state languages of the republic, regardless of nationality.
"No offense of Muslim netatars can be spoken of," Mr. Muhammetshin emphasized, explaining that the sermon itself "is not a compulsory, the main part of prayer."
At the same time, the prayer itself will still be read in Arabic, in the mosques there will be lectures and lessons in Russian.
At the same time, Rafik Muhammetshin said “U” that there was no serious threat of the expulsion of the Tatar language from the mosques.
In addition to Russian and Tatar, other languages, such as Uzbek or Tajik, according to him, are not used in sermons in the republic.
The decision of the DUM was actively supported by the executive committee of the World Congress of Tatars (WTC).
The head of the executive committee of the VCT Rinat Zakirov said: "Mosques are an important part of our national life".
It would be sad if the Tatar language had gone out of this sphere.
He noted that preaching only in the Tatar language "the desire of the imams themselves", but in the executive committee of the WCT "consider it right".
The "U" imams interviewed, who preached in Russian, are ready to execute the decision of the DUM, but believe that the parishioners will have difficulties in understanding the clergy.
Both Russians and Tatars go to the mosque.
Many do not understand the language.
Of course, they will be sad.
"It will have to be rebuilt," says Imam of the Bournaev Mosque Farhat Mavletdinov.
According to him, sermons in Russian are even closer to many Tatars, because "Russian in schools and kindergartens, on the radio - everywhere is original".
However, he believes that the mosque will be able to continue lessons and lectures in Russian, which are held on other days.
We rely on God.
Allah will show you the way out of this situation,” he concluded.
About 60% of us do not know the Tatar language.
These are both Uzbeks, Tajiks, and Azerbaijanis.
There are many foreign students coming to us: Africans, Arabs.
“That’s why we’ve been switching to Russian for four years,” the imam says.
He believes that in the Tatar language, sermons will “reach a narrower circle and will not reach the entire audience.”
But we will obey the decision of the plenary.
The result of the preaching will be different.
But time will tell.
“For example, it will only be easier for me, because Tatar is my native language,” said Gabdulla Galiullin.
Former FSIN Director Sued
The Moscow Prosecutor’s Office approved the indictment on the investigated GSU SCR criminal case on the theft of budget funds allocated for the needs of the FSIN of Russia.
Before the court will appear the former head of the prison department Alexander Reimer and his deputy, which caused FSIN damages in the amount of more than 2.7 billion rubles.
The Metropolitan Prosecutor’s Office has sent a criminal case to the Zamoskvoretsky District Court in relation to the former director of the FSIN of Russia, Alexander Reimer, his former deputy Nikolay Krivolapov, as well as the director of the FGUP “Center of Information Technology Support and Communications of the Federal Service for the Execution of Penalties” (FTOU).
Depending on the role and the degree of participation in the commission of crimes, they are accused of GSU SCR on Moscow under article 3 of article 285 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (abuse of office powers, which has caused serious consequences), article 4 of article 159 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (fraud committed by the group using its own service).
In addition, Krivolapov is accused under Article 222 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (illegal acquisition and storage of ammunition).
According to the SCR, in 2010-2012, these individuals fraudulently hijacked the budget funds allocated by the FSIN to provide the agency with electronic monitoring systems for controlled persons, so-called electronic bracelets.
For the theft of budget money, the group members developed a scheme according to which the company under their control, FGUP CITOS, with which the relevant government contracts were concluded, produced technical means of control and supervision, including "electronic bracelets", and implemented at prices that were exaggerated several times.
Despite the fact that FGUP CITOS did not have production equipment, buildings, facilities for the placement of production capacities that allow to create a completed cycle of production of "electronic bracelets", five state contracts for the amount of more than 3.3 billion rubles were concluded between it and the FSIN of Russia.
As a result of this scheme, more than 2 billion rubles were stolen from the accounts of the Samaritan branch of the FGUP, of which 1.2 billion rubles were stolen.
According to the investigation, more than 140 million rubles of cash disbursed was personally received by Mr. Reimer in his office from one of the accomplices, whose criminal case was allocated to a separate proceeding.
Nikolay Krivolapov, who participated in the machinations, was found unknown the origin of the ammunition to the award pistol, which allowed him to file an additional charge.
In this case, the volume of which amounted to 133 volumes, the FSIN filed a claim for compensation for material damage in the amount of 2.7 billion rubles to the accused.
Footballer Hakan Shukur is suspected of involvement in the coup.
The Turkish authorities issued a warrant for the arrest of the former footballer, and then a member of parliament Hakan Shukur, and conducted searches in two houses of his family.
The star of Turkish football in the 1990s and early 2000s, attacker Hakan Shukur is being sought by the country's authorities in connection with an attempted coup last month.
Forward, who quit his sports career in 2008, is accused of belonging to an "armed terrorist group".
It is about the movement "Hizmet" - a society associated with the famous Turkish religious figure and oppositionist Fethullah Gülen.
It is President Erdogan who considers him the organizer of the military coup attempt that took place on July 15.
Fethullah Gülen lives in the United States, the Turkish authorities demand his extradition.
According to local media, today was issued a warrant for the arrest of Hakan Shukur, police have already conducted searches in two houses, which belong to the family of the former footballer.
According to the investigation, the organization of Fethullah Gülen, in addition to Hakan Shukur himself, included his father.
However, neither the former footballer himself nor his relatives were there.
He and his family now live in the United States.
As a footballer, Hakan Shukur defended the colors of several Turkish clubs and played for the national team.
He spent most of his career in Galatasaray.
The list of foreign clubs includes the Italian "Torino", "Inter" and "Palermo", as well as the English "Blackburn".
He has not spent more than one season in any of them.
Hakan Shukur is still Turkey’s most successful striker: he has 112 matches for the national team and 51 goals.
In 2013, Hakan Shukur resigned from his deputy post because of a corruption investigation into Erdogan’s party and his immediate entourage.
According to the Turkish newspaper Hurriyet, a warrant for the arrest of at least 42 journalists was issued in Turkey on July 25.
They are accused of facilitating a military coup and of linking them to the U.S.-based opposition Islamic preacher Fethullah Gülen.
Given the severity of the charges, media officials can face lengthy prison terms ranging from ten years to several life sentences.
