The Russian Copper Company (RMK) is ready to take on social responsibility and pay more attention to the environmental aspects of its business.
This is confirmed, for example, by the fact that the RMK has undertaken the modernization of one of the oldest and environmentally "dirty" enterprises in the country - the Karabakh Melting Plant.
The Karabakh Melting Plant was founded by an English joint stock company headed by Leslie Urkwart in 1910.
In Soviet times, it was a significant industrial enterprise for the country's economy, and it actually provided the vitality of the entire city.
However, in the 1990s, due to financial problems, production was halted, which resulted in serious social problems in Karabakh.
In 1998, it was decided to resume the work of the Karabakh Melting Plant.
It was also necessary to solve one of the main problems of the Karabakh plant - environmental.
By the early 2000s, Karabakh was already sadly known as an environmental disaster zone.
The situation at Karabashmedi began to change in 2004, after the company went under the control of the Russian Copper Company.
The company began to modernize production, which began to gradually reduce the environmental burden on the environment.
This was recently noted by the governor of the Chelyabinsk region, Boris Dubrovsky, who visited Karabakhmed in the first few days of July.
The head of the Southern Urals called the grand changes that have occurred with the enterprise since Karabakhmed transferred to the RMK group.
The main event for the modernization of "Karabashmedi" in recent years was the construction of a new sulphuric acid workshop, which allows to capture up to 99.9% of metallurgical gases.
According to the president of the Russian copper company Vsevolod Levin, the volume of investments in this project amounted to about 7 billion rubles.
The next stage of modernization of Karabashmed JSC is the reconstruction of the converter terminal.
Replacement of three converters, injectors, gas pipeline is scheduled for the end of 2017.
The cost of the project is 2.5 billion rubles.
In addition, at the end of 2016, it is planned to launch a new industrial sewage treatment plant worth 1 billion rubles.
In turn, the amount of taxes deducted to the budget of the city of Karabakh will also increase.
