Bulgaria shows inflation for the first time in 8 months
Inflation in Bulgaria was 1% per month in July, according to national statistics.
This is the highest figure in years (since June 2012) and the first above zero since October last year, when a positive 0.2% was shown.
The average annual inflation, measured by the CPI, for the last 12 months (August 2015 - July 2016) compared to the previous 12 months (August 2014 - July 2015) was -0.8%.
The consumer price index in July 2016 compared to June 2016 was 101.0%, i.e. monthly inflation was 1.0%.
The inflation rate since the beginning of the year (July 2016 compared to December 2015) was -0.2%, and annual inflation in July 2016 compared to July 2015 was -0.2%.
In July 2016, compared to the previous month, there was an increase in the price of the following consumer goods groups: food and soft drinks (1.7%); transport (1.8%); recreation and culture (6.3%); restaurants and hotels (1.2%); other goods and services (0.3%).
Prices declined for clothing and footwear (2.2%); furniture, household appliances and regular maintenance (0.5%); and health (0.1%).
Prices remained at the same level as the previous month for alcoholic beverages and tobacco; housing, water, electricity, gas and other fuels; communications systems; and education.
Snapchat Anime Effect Criticized as a Cartoon for Asians
Snapchat claims that this filter is inspired by anime, but some reviewers say it is racially tactless.
With the help of the "Lins" tool, Snapchat allows about 150 million users a day to change reality and play with individuality in ways that border on absurdity.
You can turn yourself into a pineapple, a dog or a character to paint Roy Liechtenstein.
Lenses are rough, twisting tools that create more than 30 million adjusted selfies a day.
Any mistakes quickly become well-known.
Snapchat lenses have been criticized in the past when they were accused of advertising dark facial skin or encouraging whitened faces as an ideal of beauty.
So when some users were offered a lens this week that gave them bent eyes, curved teeth and swollen cheeks, some critics thought it was a racist caricature of Asians — “yellows.”
And they wondered if these recurring contradictions pointed to a more serious company problem related to diversity.
On Wednesday, reports spread, followed by outrage in reports on The Verge and Motherboard, the day after Snapchat said it had removed the feature.
The company commented: the lens was designed as a tribute to the characters of the anime, not as a cartoon for Asians.
But to experts who know about racism, the lens reminded of offensive stereotypes in action.
Others completely rejected the comparison with anime.
In an email, Grace Sparapani, a Korean-American arts student whose tweets about the photos were actively shared, said the lens was “insulting and at least embarrassing.”
She added that "it's hard to argue with the comparison side by side of a very rough cartoon on Asians and filter effects.
This shows that the filter is not just yellowish, but highly demeaning yellowish.
Snapchat is not the only company that crosses these cultural bridges.
American culture seems engaged in an endless struggle for diversity and inclusiveness, ranging from corporate meeting rooms to Hollywood and the devices we all carry with us.
And the huge audience of young people on Snapchat — who are more racially diverse than their older generation — may mean that they are more likely to be expected to understand.
When one of Snapchat’s lenses creates an image that is offensive to the user, then, in an interview Thursday, 25-year-old Katie Zhou said, “this course of events is much harder to go unnoticed than it was before.”
On Thursday, Zhou, a product manager and engineer working for Medium, decided to delete her Snapchat account and urged others to do the same.
