"Generation protests" in Ethiopia, longtime ally of the United States
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Protesters demanding political change in Ethiopia have faced fierce opposition from the government.
Eyewitnesses say dozens of protesters were fatally wounded during clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia really on the brink of a rift?
Over the past decade, it has been one of the most stable countries in Africa, a steadfast ally of the West with a fast-growing economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have rocked the country, spreading to an increasing number of its territories.
In the past week alone, thousands of people have taken to the streets demanding radical political change.
According to human rights defenders, the government’s reaction was brutal.
Eyewitnesses said police officers shot dozens of unarmed demonstrators.
Video footage of the protests, allegedly taken at the end of last year or earlier this year, shows how security officers beat young people with sticks when they put their hands on the wall.
The United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights now calls for a thorough investigation.
“It’s always been hard to keep this country from breaking up, and it’s going to be even harder,” said Rashid Abdi, head of the African Horn project at the international research crisis group.
Ethiopia is the second most populous country in Africa after Nigeria, and its stability is maintained by the West.
U.S. military and intelligence services are working closely with Ethiopians to combat terrorist threats in the region, especially in Somalia, and virtually no country in Africa receives such support from the West.
Ethiopia’s economy is developing at an impressive rate.
Its infrastructure has improved considerably - there is even a new suburban train in the capital Addis Ababa.
And its streets are usually quiet, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia was hardly a model of democracy – human rights organizations constantly mention government repression – the opposition in the state was suppressed by the fact that the dissidents were actually silenced.
Many of them were exiled, imprisoned, killed or exiled to remote deserts.
But that could change.
“If people are constantly oppressed and left with no choice but to protest, there will be an uprising,” said Seium Teshome, a professor at the university in central Ethiopia.
All young people are protesting.
The generation protested.
Complaints are numerous, ranging from land use to the seizure of power by a government coalition.
After the widely criticized elections last year, the government party and its allies have completely displaced the opposition and now control 100 percent of Parliament.
At the same time, tensions along the border with Eritrea are growing; the struggle for this uncertain, controversial border took hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups that have been more or less destroyed in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to use the riots and rearm themselves.
A number of factors explain why the bitter feelings, which have been boiling in the depths of the soul for several years, are erupting now.
The first, apparently, completely harmless: smartphones.
Only in the last couple of years, a large number of Ethiopians have been able to communicate on social networks, as cheap smartphones have become commonplace, and internet service has become better.
Even when the government shuts down access to Facebook and Twitter, as it often happens, especially during protests, many people still find the opportunity to communicate through proxy servers that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said that this is how they organized the protests.
The second is that there is more solidarity between Oromo and Amhara, the two largest Ethiopian ethnic groups.
Oromo and Amhara are not natural allies.
Over the centuries, Amhara from Ethiopia’s predominantly Christian highland areas flourished in politics and business, exploiting Oromo, many of whom are Muslim and live in lowland areas.
But it also changes.
“We will act together under a single principle,” said Mulatu Gemechu, the leader of Oromo.
The largest protests took place in the areas of Amhara and Oromo.
Many of Amhara and Oromo feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, which accounts for about 6% of the population and which controls military and intelligence services, trade and politics.
The third cause of concern is the loss of Meles Zenawi.
Meles, a former rebel leader, served as Ethiopia's prime minister for 17 years, until his death from an unknown illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could foresee danger.
Analysts claim that he particularly skillfully recognized the first signs of discontent and used intelligence to obtain data and defeat opponents.
“The current regime lacks common sense,” said Abdi, a conflict analyst.
The new Prime Minister of Ethiopia, Hailemariam Desalen, appeared from nowhere and took the place of Meles.
Unlike Meles, who was native to the Tigray region in northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam is a southerner.
Analysts say he does not enjoy the trust of security services controlled by the Tigray.
Many fear that as a result, it will lead to even more bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia experienced such turmoil was in 2005, after thousands of people protested against what analysts said was apparently an election that the government stunned and then falsified the results.
In the ensuing repressions, many Protestants were killed, albeit in smaller numbers than in recent months, and this period of turmoil passed relatively quickly.
Development experts expressed gratitude to the leaders of Ethiopia for the far-sighted development of infrastructure, such as a new intercity train and significant achievements in the fight against poverty.
But it is clear that this has not stopped the growth of domestic discontent with the Ethiopian government.
And it takes on a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, a city in Amhara, attacked enterprises owned by Tigray, and anti-Tygray hatred on social media is becoming widespread.
Analysts say the protesters are putting the United States and other Western allies in an awkward position.
The U.S. government used Ethiopia as a base for unmanned flights over neighboring Somalia, although it recently announced that it had closed the base.
On the one hand, it is clear that the West wants to support democracy, but on the other hand, it does not want its ally to lose power in an already unstable region.
"And it will be difficult to pass through this stretched rope," Abdi said.
