Adblock Plus, Facebook play "cat-mouse" on the issue of ad blocking
For companies that make money from online advertising, attempts to circumvent ad-blocking software are a cat-mouse game, according to one of the companies that creates such software.
On Thursday, just a few days after Facebook announced it was going to block ad blockers on its desktop version of the site, Adblock Plus posted a blog post that users could update their filters in the program to block ads on the social network again.
On Tuesday, Facebook announced that the desktop version of the site is changing the layer around its ads, making it harder for ad blockers to recognize which parts of the page are ads.
But Adblock now claims that it was able to circumvent the new code.
In a blog post, Adblock spokesman Ben Williams wrote that “this kind of mutual struggle between the community of open-source ad blockers and those who try to bypass it has been going on since the invention of ad blocking,” and it is possible that Facebook will present its own solution in the near future.
The fact that the world’s largest social network has entered the fight is a clear sign of how big the ad blockers have become for the industry.
Approximately 200 million people worldwide use ad blockers, according to last year’s Pagefair and Adobe survey; almost four times more than those who used such software in 2013.
Given the 1.3 billion daily active users who visit Facebook via mobile devices, mobile advertising now accounts for 84 percent of Facebook’s advertising revenue.
However, the company is hunting for ad blockers on the desktop version, as mobile ad blockers are ineffective in Facebook mobile apps for the social network and Instagram, according to the representative.
But still, the advertising in the desktop version is a profitable enough article for Facebook to consider such a step a profitable investment.
Also on Thursday, Facebook announced that it is going to update its “advertising preferences” tool to give people more control over how they are targeted by advertising.
Facebook said on Thursday that the new Adblock filters are a cause for concern as they will also block some non-advertising content on the site.
“This will not be a positive experience for people, and we plan to solve this problem,” a Facebook spokesperson said in an official email.
Ad blockers are a rough tool, so instead we’ve focused on creating tools like Ad Preferences to hand over control to people.
A woman moved on a Swiss highway in an episode of apparent suicide
