Police are calling for witnesses after the woman was moved by several vehicles on the highway early Thursday morning in an apparent suicide attempt.
The incident took place on the A1 near Morge in the canton of Dans immediately after midnight on Thursday.
The woman lay on the road in the dark "in a gesture of despair" and was hit by several vehicles, the police said in a statement.
Apparently trying to kill themselves, the victim, a Swiss woman aged 49, was hit by several vehicles, including a truck.
She died on the spot.
Several of the drivers involved have already been questioned, but the identity of some has not yet been established, police said, calling on them and someone else who witnessed the incident to respond.
A criminal case was initiated, a "logical" step in such a situation, said lawyer Gilles Hofstetter Le Tribune de Genève.
However, it remains to be seen whether any of the drivers involved will be charged.
Was it possible to avoid a hit?
That’s what the prosecutor has to determine,” Hofstetter said.
Two other similar cases over the past five years suggest that drivers will not be held responsible.
In each case - both of which involve a person walking in the dark on the highway - a verdict was issued that drivers cannot expect an accidental meeting with a pedestrian on the highway in the middle of the night, the newspaper reports.
Last year, an officer was acquitted of causing death by negligence after she struck and killed a man lying on the A1 off Pierne at night in August 2014.
The 22-year-old victim drank and lost consciousness on the road, the court heard.
