NASA's Climate Model: Venus Was Once Inhabited
Venus may have once been inhabited, according to estimates from NASA’s new climate model.
Scientists from the Goddard Space Research Institute in Nassau have developed a model for studying the past of Venus, using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climatologists.
The model was designed to determine if on Venus, with its hot anhydrous surface and atmosphere oversaturated with carbon dioxide, could ever exist conditions similar to Earth’s.
Scientists have previously assumed that the small speed of rotation of Venus is due to its dense atmosphere.
But the latest modelling suggests that Venus may have had a loose atmosphere, similar to Earth’s, and is still spinning slowly.
The model also looked at the topography of early Venus.
There were probably more arid regions on the planet than on Earth, but once there was enough water and enough geographical variability to create conditions for life and prevent rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also benefited from the sun, which was 30 percent dim.
“According to the GISS model, the slow rotation of Venus puts its day side on the sun for almost two months at a time,” GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio explained in a press release.
This heats the planet’s surface and produces rain, which creates a thick layer of clouds acting as an umbrella protecting the planet’s surface from a substantial portion of the sun’s heat.
The result is average climate temperatures, which, surprisingly, are several degrees colder than today on Earth.
The model shows the history of Venus, similar to the evolution previously assumed by planetary experts.
Despite the fact that Venus may have once been inhabited, it has been exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet radiation for several billion years.
Her oceans evaporated and her water vapor was burned by ultraviolet radiation.
When its hydrogen flew away, there was only a dense atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a deadly greenhouse effect — that is, Venus, as we know it today.
The researchers shared the results of their new Venus climate model in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
