Kepler Measures the Speed of Rotation of Stars in the Pleiades Cluster
The latest mission of the Kepler Space Telescope helped astronomers compile the most complete catalog of the rotational speeds of stars in the Pleiades cluster.
The new data help astronomers understand why stars in the cluster rotate at different speeds, as well as how periods of rotation relate to the formation of planets.
“We hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters, we will learn more about the relationship between the mass of a star, its age and even the history of its solar system,” Louise Riball, a researcher at the Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis, told the press.
The Pleiades cluster is 445 light-years from Earth.
Many stars in the cluster are now only reaching maturity; they were born about 125 million years ago.
They are spinning as fast as they will ever be again.
At their peak rotational speeds, these adult stars emit large amounts of stellar wind.
Traveling through the magnetic fields of stars, these winds have a inhibiting effect on the stars.
As the star ages, its rotational speed begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the speed of rotation of each star by tracking the time between the appearance of recognizable stellar spots, such as solar spots.
The latest catalog of rotational speeds suggests that more massive stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Fishball compares stars to dancers: larger ones make pirouettes slower than smaller ones.
“In the ballet of the Pleiades, we observe that those that rotate slowly are usually more massive, while those that rotate faster are usually very light stars,” said Fisher.
Since the Pleiades cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing the properties of stars with rotational speeds.
“The Pleiades star cluster provides a starting point for theoretical models of star rotation, both young and old,” said Ryball.
We still want to learn a lot about how, where and why stars slow down their rotation and hang their “dance shoes” on the nail, figuratively speaking.
Fisher and her colleagues have detailed their latest analysis of the speeds of the Pleiades in three new articles that will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
