Native to Angola and South Africa, Namibia suffered greatly during the long struggle against apartheid.
However, since independence from South Africa in 1990, the country with a population of 2.4 million has achieved tremendous success, especially in the last few years.
The main reason for Namibia's success is that the government pays great attention to education.
While people in developed countries take for granted free primary and secondary education, in many poor countries, secondary and even primary schools require tuition fees.
Moreover, governments are often advised to introduce tuition fees to “refund costs”.
However, in Namibia, primary schools are free of charge.
Secondary education has been free of charge since 2015.
The country’s authorities are also actively working in other important areas.
Efforts to eradicate malaria have reduced the number of annual cases by 97% over the past decade.
Despite the international trend of rising inequality, it is shrinking in Namibia.
Compared to 1993, the Gini coefficient, a standard indicator of income inequality, fell by 15 points.
Then, 23 years ago, this figure was one of the highest in the world.
The poverty rate fell from 69 per cent in 1993 to less than 30 per cent.
The number of people living in extreme poverty (less than $1.90 a day) has also declined, from nearly 53% to less than 23%.
Namibia also has Africa’s highest rating for freedom of speech, according to Reporters Without Borders.
The country is well ahead of the United States and other wealthy nations.
In addition, the country has a favourable ranking - one of the highest in Africa - in the "Corruption Perceptions Index", which is made up of human rights defenders from Transparency International.
Even now that commodity prices are falling, Namibia has managed to maintain a high rate of growth.
At the same time, the debt-to-GDP ratio is around 25%, which is less than 1/3 of the debt level in the United States and most European countries.
There are, of course, some problems in Namibia.
The unemployment rate, at least by traditional assessment methods, remains fairly high - nearly 28 per cent.
And like other countries in the region, Namibia has a high rate of HIV/AIDS - almost 17% of the population is infected.
According to the World Bank, Namibia is one of the countries with higher incomes than the average, but the authorities insist that their state is actually a developing country.
Namibia is undoubtedly facing some of the difficulties inherent in underdeveloped economies.
The state has to develop a very large and arid country with a small population.
On the territory of the country in the deserts live isolated nomadic tribes of hunter-gatherers, which in one way or another should be integrated into modern society, without losing their identity.
Integrating people who were on the periphery of the world economy a quarter century ago is not an easy task for any country.
For Namibia, it is even more difficult: just like any other country in the world, it faces the consequences of climate change.
However, Namibia has not thought to drop its hands, the country solves the problems that it faces.
Almost immediately after independence, the authorities began to create a diversified economy and a cohesive society.
It is noteworthy that competing political factions have come together to work for the common good.
Indeed, Namibia provides cheap medical care not only to its own citizens, but also to its neighbors.
About 15-20% of visitors to health facilities in the northern areas of Namibia are Angolan citizens.
No one in Namibia is talking about building a wall that would separate the country from its poor and corrupt neighbors.
The Namibians realized that the neighbors did not choose, and therefore decided not to conflict with them, but to cooperate - to share scarce water resources, to participate in regional medical projects, to encourage investment and exchange of students.
In addition, the Government of Namibia has rightly held that rich natural resources can easily become a curse, contributing to the enrichment of few at the expense of many.
The authorities understand that revenues from Namibia’s natural resources need to be invested in infrastructure and production facilities.
They also realize that it would be irresponsible not to seek the maximum profit from the sale of the country’s resources, and are reviewing investment laws and mining contracts to make sure it is.
Transparency is crucial to this process, which is why strong government support for freedom of speech is so important.
As the head of state, Hage Heingob, noted, the media often say what he does not like.
But after fighting for freedom from apartheid in South Africa, Namibia must defend the freedoms it has gained, the president says.
Not all of Namibia's key resources are exhaustive.
Some - such as fishing - are considered renewable, and the government is making every effort to preserve and strengthen them.
Every year more than one million foreign tourists visit the country.
Namibia shows that even those countries that begin with serious shortcomings - racism, colonialism, inequality and low levels of development - can stand on the way to common prosperity.
Its achievement deserves international recognition and imitation.
Many have heard of the "Gold of Varna" - the oldest man-made gold objects (4600 - 4200 BC).
Perhaps this was the loudest archaeological sensation of the 1970s: in Bulgaria, during the excavations of the Varna Necropolis, a fantastic number of gold artifacts were found - more than three thousand total weight 6 kilograms.
Only one burial known as the "grave No. 43" extracted 990 gold items weighing more than 1.5 kg.
However, the official status of the world’s oldest gold may soon pass to the invisible gem found by archaeologists in July this year.
And again in Bulgaria - in a prehistoric settlement known as Tell Yunacite.
Unlike Varna, a port city, Tell Yunacite is located far from the sea, near the village of Yunacite of Pazardzhik district.
The pearl is a golden stripe wrapped in a ring.
Yavor Boyadzhiyev, the head of the excavation at Telle Yunacite, dated the find to 4600 BC and stated that it was at least 200 years older than Varna’s gold.
The treasures of Varna, we will remind, date from about the same period, 4600 - 4200 BC.
There are currently no technologies that allow the metal to be dated with impeccable accuracy.
How do you know which gold is the oldest?
Apparently, Professor Boyadzhiev knows more than he told Reuters: “I am absolutely sure that Yunacite gold is older than Varna gold.”
This is an extremely important finding: it is a tiny object, but it is large enough to occupy an appropriate place in history.
In an interview with Reuters, Boyadjiev said that in the near future, scientists will analyze the composition of the metal, as well as re-examine and more thoroughly the archaeological layer where the gold artifact was found.
This will help to date the beads with the greatest possible accuracy.
The location of the find also explains a lot.
Tell Yunacite is a famous settlement, even if you have never heard of it.
Today, Tell-Yunacite is considered the oldest "city" in Europe.
Tell was founded by descendants of people who migrated to Europe from Anatolia (modern Turkey) in the 7th millennium BC.
During the following centuries, metalworking developed rapidly in the region, from the development of the first metallurgical skills to the creation of a full-fledged industry.
In the domestic historiography for this archaeological community there is a special name: Balkan-Carpathian metallurgical province.
In the 5th millennium BC, urban settlements began to emerge around metalworking centers.
They are now called the oldest cities in Europe.
Of these, Tell Unazite is perhaps the oldest, as artifacts were found here in 4900 BC.
I would call Tell Unazite a prototype of a modern city, although it is a very ancient settlement, even when compared to Mesopotamia.
“This place is a thousand years older than Shumer,” says Boyajiev, referring to the generally accepted view that urban culture originated in southern Mesopotamia, modern-day Iraq.
It was there that the first cities in the usual sense of the word arose.
The excavations of Tella Yunacita have been carried out since 1976.
During this time, archaeologists have excavated almost 12 hectares, which is about a third of the estimated total settlement area.
The remains of the fortress wall, which once reached three meters in height, were found.
There is little left of houses and workshops, but archaeologists clearly distinguish streets, public buildings, urban dense buildings, a "business center" and residential outskirts.
Tell Yunacite is often called the "City of Birds": dozens of clay figurines of birds have been found here.
All birds are depicted in a state of rest, hence the assumption that they were not decorative objects, but an object of local cult.
The "City of Birds" was destroyed around 4100 BC - possibly by Indo-European tribes coming from the northeast.
The nomads had no cities, but they had horses and weapons.
The three-meter stronghold walls did not stop them.
Archaeologists have found obvious signs of brutal slaughter: inside the houses were found the remains of old men, women and children with traces of wounds inflicted by war axes.
New findings and new facts appear every year, changing the usual notions about the ancient history of mankind.
Bulgarian archaeologists are increasingly talking not about individual cultures, but about the “lost” first civilization of Europe, born in the Balkans.
A powerful stimulus in the search for this civilization was the "gold of Varna", found relatively recently, in 1972.
It is logical that the gold luxury of Varna should have been preceded by something - something like a tiny gold beads created in Tella Yunacita.
